[30;1m589 | [0m[35mThe insight we'll make use of here is, essentially, that the logs written by a single server can be[0m
[30;1m590 | [0m[35msummarized with a fraction of the resources of the server.  For starters, we don't need to write as[0m
[30;1m591 | [0m[35mmuch data to say a log has data as we write to that log.  If each append to a log is approximately[0m
[30;1m592 | [0m[35m4 kB+ (a reasonable document size with a vector), we can track the dirty log by name using at most[0m
[30;1m593 | [0m[35m48 B; an 85x reduction.  But it goes further---we only need to persist that 48B record once per[0m
[30;1m594 | [0m[35mfragment write, not once per append.[0m

[30;1m566 | [0m[35m## Serverless Behavior[0m
[30;1m567 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m568 | [0m[35mFirst off, wal3 is intended to run multiple wal3 instances in parallel and open at the same time.[0m
[30;1m569 | [0m[35mThe over head per wal3 instance is single digit megabytes (manifest and a buffer of writes), meaning[0m
[30;1m570 | [0m[35mthat we can handle hundreds or thousands of concurrent logs per server.  We cannot open every log[0m
[30;1m571 | [0m[35mfor every customer on a single machine and have it fit memory.  We will have to open and close logs.[0m

[30;1m394 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m395 | [0m[35mTo side-step this problem we will introduce intentional fragmentation of the manifest and snapshots[0m
[30;1m396 | [0m[35mto align to the garbage collection interval.  This will guarantee that at most one interval worth of[0m

[30;1m398 | [0m[35msuch that they are pre-aligned to garbage collection boundaries.[0m

[30;1m364 | [0m[35mall forseeable current requirements.  20-25 pointers in the root, or 2kB are all that's needed to[0m
[30;1m365 | [0m[35mcapture a log that's more than a petabyte in size.  Compare that to 5k pointers or 329kB for a[0m
[30;1m366 | [0m[35msingle manifest.  We're dealing with kilobytes per manifest for a log that's petabytes, but when[0m
[30;1m367 | [0m[35meach manifest targets < 1MB in size, the difference at write time is apparent in the latency.[0m

[30;1m310 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m311 | [0m[35m## Manifest Compaction[0m
[30;1m312 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m313 | [0m[35mThe manifest is a chain of writes, each of which adds a new file to the previous write.  Look at[0m
[30;1m314 | [0m[35mthis another way and the number of bytes written to object storage for the manifest is quadratic in[0m
[30;1m315 | [0m[35mthe number of writes to the manifest.  This is a problem because each manifest write is[0m
[30;1m316 | [0m[35mincrementally more expensive than the previous write.[0m
[30;1m317 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1621[0m[34m of [0m[33m2364[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m184 | [0m[35mCursors are integral to utility of wal3 to Chroma, so we'll briefly revisit how Chroma's log works[0m
[30;1m185 | [0m[35mtoday to see how it could work with Chroma.  In Chroma, the log maintains two positions:  The[0m
[30;1m186 | [0m[35mcompaction offset and the tail of the log.  At any time, a reader must brute force or scan the data[0m
[30;1m187 | [0m[35mon the log to be strongly consistent.  To counteract this from growing without bound, compaction[0m
[30;1m188 | [0m[35mperiodically rewrites a snapshot of the data that merges the last compaction's output with all data[0m
[30;1m189 | [0m[35mon the log.[0m

[30;1m86 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m89 | [0m[35m- pruned:  A setsum of the log data that has been pruned and thrown away.  The fragments of[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35m  the log plus the `pruned` value must equal `setsum`[0m

[30;1m78 | [0m[35massociative and commutative hash function that is used to verify the integrity of the log.  Because[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35mof the way the hash function is constructed, it is possible to compute a new setsum from an existing[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35msetsum and the setsum of a new fragment.  This allows us to get cryptographic-strength integrity[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mchecking of the log.  We go into this at length in the verifiability section below.[0m

[30;1m627 | [0m[35m## Scaling[0m
[30;1m628 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m629 | [0m[35mChanging the number of logs requires a hashing scheme that maps N compactor nodes onto M log service[0m
[30;1m630 | [0m[35mnodes.  Because the dirty log doesn't drop that a collection is dirty until it advances, it suffices[0m
[30;1m631 | [0m[35mto make every compactor pull from every log during times of change.[0m
[30;1m632 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m633 | [0m[35mI'd like to make it more efficient than that.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1631[0m[34m of [0m[33m2364[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m566 | [0m[35m## Serverless Behavior[0m
[30;1m567 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m568 | [0m[35mFirst off, wal3 is intended to run multiple wal3 instances in parallel and open at the same time.[0m
[30;1m569 | [0m[35mThe over head per wal3 instance is single digit megabytes (manifest and a buffer of writes), meaning[0m
[30;1m570 | [0m[35mthat we can handle hundreds or thousands of concurrent logs per server.  We cannot open every log[0m
[30;1m571 | [0m[35mfor every customer on a single machine and have it fit memory.  We will have to open and close logs.[0m
[30;1m572 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1635[0m[34m of [0m[33m2364[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/chromadb-1.0.4/rust/wal3/README.md[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m529 | [0m[35madjusted so that every manifest is checksummed end-to-end with a checksum nearly as strong as sha3.[0m
[30;1m530 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m531 | [0m[35mEach time a new fragment is written to the log, the fragment gets checksummed.  This checksum gets[0m
[30;1m532 | [0m[35madded to the checksum in the manifest.  Each time a fragment is garbage collected, the checksum of[0m
[30;1m533 | [0m[35mthe fragment gets removed from the manifest.[0m
[30;1m534 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m535 | [0m[35mThe checksum itself has the following properties:[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1636[0m[34m of [0m[33m2364[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/chromadb-1.0.4/rust/wal3/README.md[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m528 | [0m[35mThe verification story is simple:  A log has a cryptographic checksum that can be incrementally[0m
[30;1m529 | [0m[35madjusted so that every manifest is checksummed end-to-end with a checksum nearly as strong as sha3.[0m
[30;1m530 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m531 | [0m[35mEach time a new fragment is written to the log, the fragment gets checksummed.  This checksum gets[0m
[30;1m532 | [0m[35madded to the checksum in the manifest.  Each time a fragment is garbage collected, the checksum of[0m
[30;1m533 | [0m[35mthe fragment gets removed from the manifest.[0m
[30;1m534 | [0m[35m[0m

   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m

[30;1m465 | [0m[35mA writer that fails will fail at any step in the process of writing to object storage.  The write[0m
[30;1m466 | [0m[35mprotocol is such that until a manifest is written to refer to the new fragment, the fragment is not[0m
[30;1m467 | [0m[35mconsidered durable.  In the event a fragment gets "orphaned" because the manifest fails, it will be[0m
[30;1m468 | [0m[35mrewritten by the next valid writer.  This means that a writer can crash at any time and restart, and[0m
[30;1m469 | [0m[35mthe log will have garbage, but not refer to the garbage.[0m
[30;1m470 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m289 | [0m[35mGarbage collection is a separate process that runs in the background:[0m
[30;1m290 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m291 | [0m[35m0.  Read all cursors and the all manifests.[0m
[30;1m292 | [0m[35m1.  From the cursors, select the minimum timestamp time across all cursors as the garbage collection[0m
[30;1m293 | [0m[35m    cutoff.[0m
[30;1m294 | [0m[35m2.  Write a list of fragments that hold data strictly less than the cutoff.[0m
[30;1m295 | [0m[35m3.  Run a verifier that checks the list of fragments to delete.[0m

[30;1m184 | [0m[35mCursors are integral to utility of wal3 to Chroma, so we'll briefly revisit how Chroma's log works[0m
[30;1m185 | [0m[35mtoday to see how it could work with Chroma.  In Chroma, the log maintains two positions:  The[0m
[30;1m186 | [0m[35mcompaction offset and the tail of the log.  At any time, a reader must brute force or scan the data[0m
[30;1m187 | [0m[35mon the log to be strongly consistent.  To counteract this from growing without bound, compaction[0m
[30;1m188 | [0m[35mperiodically rewrites a snapshot of the data that merges the last compaction's output with all data[0m
[30;1m189 | [0m[35mon the log.[0m
